<a href="http://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/Business-News/New-Britain-Palm-Oil-reports-disappointing-results" target="_self">http://www.foodmanufacture.co.uk/Business-News/New-Britain-Palm-Oil-repo...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In the coming years, the debate on sustainability certification of palm oil is likely to shift to the depth of the sustainability commitments incorporated into the certification requirements. New investments in palm oil production in ACP countries will need to build the future evolution of sustainability requirements into current investment plans, including with regard to potential methane capture and utilisation requirements.</p><p>Any incorporation of methane capture and utilisation requirements raises issues related to the sharing of costs and benefits of compliance along the supply chain. In the palm oil sector, sustainability certification has generally assisted in the market positioning of palm oil suppliers, but has not necessarily yielded price premiums. In the past, this left primary producers and first-stage processors generally carrying the costs of certification. Any methane capture requirement, however, would involve not only investment costs, but also potentially significant financial returns. This raises important issues related to the distribution of costs and benefits of sustainability certification requirements along palm oil supply chains.</p>
		</div>
		
